      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2>Line Heights</h2>

  <div class="type-scale">
    <div class="type-sample">
      <div class="type-sample-label">leading-tight<br>1.2</div>
      <div class="type-sample-text" style="line-height: var(--leading-tight);">
        Tight line height for headlines and display text. Use sparingly for short text blocks.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-sample">
      <div class="type-sample-label">leading-snug<br>1.375</div>
      <div class="type-sample-text" style="line-height: var(--leading-snug);">
        Snug line height for subheadings and card titles where space is limited but readability matters.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-sample">
      <div class="type-sample-label">leading-normal<br>1.5</div>
      <div class="type-sample-text" style="line-height: var(--leading-normal);">
        Normal line height for body text. This is the default for paragraphs and most UI text.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-sample">
      <div class="type-sample-label">leading-relaxed<br>1.625</div>
      <div class="type-sample-text" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Relaxed line height for long-form content, articles, and documentation where readability is paramount.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2>Usage</h2>

  <pre><code>/* Headlines */
h1 {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: var(--text-5xl);
  line-height: var(--leading-tight);
  font-weight: 700;
}

/* Body text */
p {
  font-family: var(--font-body);
  font-size: var(--text-base);
  line-height: var(--leading-normal);
}

/* Code blocks */
pre, code {
  font-family: var(--font-mono);
  font-size: var(--text-sm);
  line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
}</code></pre>
</section>
